{
  "Which of the following is an intensive property?": "",
  "Mass": "",
  "Density": "",
  "Length": "",
  "Volume": "",
  "Density does not depend on the amount of matter — a small piece of gold has the same density as a large bar. Mass, volume, and length all change when the sample size changes, making them extensive properties.": "",
  "Which of the following is an extensive property?": "",
  "Boiling point": "",
  "Color": "",
  "Mass depends on the amount of matter — doubling the sample doubles the mass. Boiling point, color, and density stay the same regardless of sample size, so they are intensive.": "",
  "Intensive properties do NOT depend on:": "",
  "The amount of matter in the sample": "",
  "The type of atoms present": "",
  "The arrangement of particles": "",
  "The chemical composition of the substance": "",
  "Intensive properties are independent of ammount — a cup of water and an ocean of water have the same boiling point, density, and color. Extensive properties (mass, volume) change with sample size.": "",
  "Boiling point is classified as:": "",
  "An extensive property": "",
  "Both intensive and extensive": "",
  "Neither intensive nor extensive": "",
  "An intensive property": "",
  "Boiling point does not change with sample size — water boils at 100°C whether you have 10 mL or 10 L. This makes it an intensive property, useful for identifying substances.": "",
  "If you cut a block of iron in half, which property changes?": "",
  "Melting point": "",
  "Cutting the block in half reduces the amount of matter, so mass and volume (extensive properties) decrease. Density, melting point, and color remain unchanged because they are intensive properties.": "",
  "Temperature is classified as:": "",
  "Temperature measures the average kinetic energy of particles, not the total — it doesn't change when you combine or divide a sample (at the same conditions). This makes it intensive.": "",
  "Which pair are both extensive properties?": "",
  "Melting point and hardness": "",
  "Mass and volume": "",
  "Temperature and pressure": "",
  "Density and color": "",
  "Mass and volume both depend on the amount of substance — doubling the sample doubles both. Density, color, temperature, pressure, melting point, and hardness are all intensive properties.": "",
  "Which property can be used to identify an unknown substance?": "",
  "Weight — because each substance has a unique weight": "",
  "Density — because it is the same regardless of sample size": "",
  "Volume — because larger samples are more visible": "",
  "Mass — because heavier substances are easier to identify": "",
  "Intensive properties like density, melting point, and boiling point are characteristic of a substance and do not change with amount. This makes them useful 'fingerprints' for identification. Mass and volume change with sample size.": "",
  "Color is classified as what type of property?": "",
  "Extensive — larger samples appear more colorful": "",
  "Neither — color is not a measurable property": "",
  "Intensive — it does not change with sample size": "",
  "Both — it depends on the substance": "",
  "A small chip of copper and a large copper bar both have the same reddish-orange color. Color does not change with the amount of substance, making it an intensive property.": "",
  "What happens to extensive properties when you combine two identical samples?": "",
  "They are cut in half": "",
  "They become intensive properties": "",
  "They double — because they depend on the amount of matter": "",
  "They stay the same — properties never change": "",
  "Extensive properties are additive. If you combine two 50 g samples of water, the total mass is 100 g and the total volume doubles. Intensive properties like temperature and density remain unchanged upon mixing identical samples.": "",
  "What is the definition of an 'intensive property'?": "",
  "A property that increases when more matter is added": "",
  "A property that requires intense energy to observe": "",
  "A property that can only be measured in a laboratory": "",
  "A property that does NOT depend on the amount of matter in the sample": "",
  "An intensive property is independent of sample size. Examples include density, boiling point, melting point, color, conductivity, and hardness. These are the same whether you have a gram or a kilogram of a substance.": "",
  "What is the definition of an 'extensive property'?": "",
  "A property that DOES depend on the amount of matter in the sample": "",
  "A property that is extensively studied in chemistry": "",
  "A property that stays the same regardless of sample size": "",
  "A property that extends over a large area": "",
  "An extensive property changes proportionally with the amount of matter. Mass, volume, length, weight, and total energy are all extensive — double the sample, double the value.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'density' and why is it classified as intensive?": "",
  "Volume per unit mass; it is intensive because gases always have the same density": "",
  "Weight divided by temperature; it is intensive because temperature is always the same": "",
  "Total mass of a substance; it is intensive because mass never changes": "",
  "Mass per unit volume (d = m/v); it is intensive because both mass and volume scale equally, so the ratio stays constant": "",
  "Density equals mass divided by volume (d = m/v). When you double the amount of substance, both mass and volume double, so their ratio remains unchanged. This makes density an intensive property useful for substance identification.": "",
  "What does 'melting point' mean, and is it intensive or extensive?": "",
  "The volume change when a solid melts; intensive — volume ratios stay constant": "",
  "The temperature at which a solid becomes a liquid; intensive — it does not depend on sample size": "",
  "The mass at which a solid begins to melt; extensive — larger objects melt at higher temperatures": "",
  "The amount of energy needed to melt a solid; extensive — more mass requires more energy": "",
  "Melting point is the temperature at which a solid transitions to liquid. It is the same regardless of sample size (1 g of ice and 1 kg of ice both melt at 0°C), making it an intensive property.": "",
  "What is 'hardness' and how is it classified?": "",
