  "The weight of a material; extensive — heavier objects feel harder": "",
  "The total force needed to break an object; extensive — larger objects are harder to break": "",
  "A measure of a material's resistance to scratching; it is intensive — a small diamond is just as hard as a large one": "",
  "Hardness measures how well a material resists being scratched or deformed. It depends on the material's internal structure and bonding, not on how much of it you have, making it an intensive property.": "",
  "What does 'conductivity' mean, and is it intensive or extensive?": "",
  "The energy released when a material conducts; extensive — it depends on wire length": "",
  "A material's ability to conduct heat or electricity; intensive — a small copper wire conducts the same per unit as a large one": "",
  "The total amount of electricity flowing through a wire; extensive — longer wires carry more current": "",
  "The speed at which heat travels; neither intensive nor extensive": "",
  "Conductivity is an intrinsic property of a material describing how well it transfers heat or electrical charge per unit dimensions. Copper has the same conductivity whether it's a wire or a block, making it intensive.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'luster'?": "",
  "The total amount of light emitted by a material; an extensive property": "",
  "The brightness of a material when heated; depends on sample size": "",
  "The way a material's surface reflects light; an intensive property": "",
  "The transparency of a material; neither intensive nor extensive": "",
  "Luster describes how a material's surface appears when it reflects light — metallic, glassy, waxy, dull, etc. A small piece of gold has the same metallic luster as a large piece, making it an intensive property.": "",
  "What does 'malleability' mean?": "",
  "The total energy needed to flatten a material; an extensive property": "",
  "The ability to dissolve in water; an intensive property of ionic compounds": "",
