  "Malleability is the ability of a material to be deformed into sheets by hammering or rolling. Gold is the most malleable metal. This property depends on the material's bonding, not on sample size, making it intensive.": "",
  "What does 'specific heat capacity' mean, and is it intensive or extensive?": "",
  "The total heat stored in a substance; extensive — larger objects store more heat": "",
  "The speed at which a substance heats up; extensive — depends on mass": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance absorbs maximum heat; neither": "",
  "The amount of energy needed to raise 1 gram of a substance by 1°C; intensive — it is the same per gram regardless of total mass": "",
  "Specific heat capacity (c) is defined per gram — water's specific heat is 4.184 J/(g·°C) whether you have 1 g or 1,000 g. Because it is normalized to mass, it does not change with sample size, making it intensive.": "",
  "What does 'ductility' mean?": "",
  "The tendency of a gas to expand; neither intensive nor extensive": "",
  "The hardness of a metallic substance; an extensive property": "",
  "The ability of a material to be drawn into thin wires without breaking; an intensive property": "",
  "The ability to resist corrosion; both intensive and extensive": "",
  "Ductility is the ability to be stretched into wires. Copper is highly ductile, which is why it is used for electrical wiring. This property depends on the material's bonding, not the amount, making it intensive.": "",
  "A jeweler has a small gold ring and a large gold bar. A customer asks, 'Does the ring have the same density as the bar?' What is the correct answer and why?": "",
  "Yes — density is an intensive property and does not change with sample size": "",
